2. Assume two threads run in parallel without synchronization between themselves. The first loops 10 times, and each time it prints a on the output. 
   The second loops 10 times, and each time it prints b on the output.
a.What is the maximum number of consecutive a’s and consecutive b’s that may appear in an execution of the program?
b.What is the minimum number of consecutive a’s and consecutive b’s that may appear in an execution of the program?
c.What synchronization mechanism we need to employ so that all a’s appear before all b’s? Show how the synchronization mechanism can be used to implement this behavior.
----------------------------
a.Maximum number of consecutive a’s and b’s: Since each thread prints 10 times, in the absence of synchronization, all a’s or all b’s can print one after the other. 
  So, the answer is 10 consecutive a’s and 10 consecutive b’s
b.Minimum number of consecutive a’s and b’s: 1 consecutive a and 1 consecutive b.
c.Synchronization mechanism: Allow all prints before allowing b prints to begin.
*********************************************************************************************************************************************
3. Explain what an atomic transaction is and give an example in which lack of atomicity results to an inconsistent state. Give details for your answer.
----------------------------
An atomic transaction is a one-time operation. It either entirely succeeds or has no effect.
Example of inconsistency: In a banking system, money transfer involves subtracting from account A and adding to account B. 
If the system crashes after subtracting fron account A but prior to account B, that means that the transaction is not finished, this results in data inconsistency.
